<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-657-075  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 657 075.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE on andamp; about ATandamp;T  Dec 3, 1990 v5 n123 p13(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Satellite transmission: California Microwave wins $1 million+ ATandamp;Tcontract for Soviet Armenian earth station.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   AT and T Network Systems International B.V. (Contracts)California Microwave Inc. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    CMIC.andO;Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsSoviet Union. Ministry of CommunicationsContractsEarth Stations.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>California Microwave's subsidiary, Satellite Transmission Systems Inc. (STS),has been awarded a $1 million+ contract from ATandamp;T-Network SystemsInternational, Hilversum, the Netherlands, to supply an INTELSAT Standard &quot;A&quot;satellite earth station to the Soviet Union's Ministry of Communications inthe Soviet Republic of Armenia.andM;STS will supply and install a 15-meter diameter antenna and associatedelectronics equipment to carry telephone traffic from Armenia to the UnitedStates and Europe.andM;The all-digital earth station will significantly improve Armenia'scommunications infrastructure which was damaged as a result of the 1988earthquake.andP;  This project is STS' first in the Soviet Union and its secondmajor satellite earth station contract to be won in the last two months froman Eastern Bloc country.andM;It is also the first time the Soviet Union's Ministry of Communications haspermitted one of its republics to buy communications equipment from anoutside supplier.andM;STS, located in Hauppauge, N.Y., designs, manufactures and installscommunications satellite terminals, equipment and networks for EUTELSAT,INTELSAT and regional satellite applications.andP;  STS has built and installedover 600 major earth stations worldwide.andM;California Microwave Inc. is a leading supplier of microwave and satellitecommunications systems.andO;</TEXT></DOC>